05069nam a22006255i 9781474470797DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20222000stk    fo  d z      eng d  a97814744707977 a10.1515/97814744707972doi  a(DE-B1597)614646  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  astkcGB-SCT 7aHIS0150002bisacsh1 aMaver, Irene, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aGlasgow /cIrene Maver. 1aEdinburgh : bEdinburgh University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (350 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tSeries Editor's Foreword -- tAcknowledgements -- tList of Illustrations -- tThe Pre-Industrial City -- t1. Glasgow prior to 1690 -- t2. The Rise of the Merchant City, 1690-1800 -- tIndustrial Transformation, 1800-1860 -- t3. The Consolidation of the Urban Economy -- t4. Pressures for Political Reform -- t5. Remaking Society -- tSecond City of the Empire, 1860-1918 -- t6. The Mature Industrial Economy -- t7. Changing Political Directions -- t8. Living in the 'Second City' -- tGlasgow Since 1918 -- t9. Industrial Decline and Economic Reorientation -- t10. Municipal and Parliamentary Politics -- t11. Social Change and Modernisation -- tFurther Reading -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aGlasgow is enshrined in the popular consciousness as a city of multiple and often contradictory identities. The 'Second City of Empire', the 'Venice of the North', 'Red Clydeside' and the 'Merchant City' are a few of the phrases that have been used to project the Glasgow image, positively and negatively. This new and extensively illustrated history explores the reality behind these stereotypes, showing Glasgow's considerable longevity as a Scottish ecclesiastical and commercial centre, yet focusing on the profound social, economic and political changes over the nineteenth and twentieth centuries.Glasgow uses much original material to illustrate the rich diversity of cultural influences that have contributed to the city's distinctive urban character. Particular emphasis is given to the people who shaped the ideas and attitudes of the times. Nineteenth-century economic success, most celebrated in the enduring mystique of Clyde shipbuilding, was associated with high-profile entrepreneurs who embodied both cosmopolitanism and individualism. At the same time, there was a passion in the projection of the progressive city and a commitment to social improvement that found expression in the assertive and increasingly collectivist brand of Glaswegian politics.Yet, as the author explains, Glasgow's strong sense of civic patriotism was often overwhelmed by the sheer intensity of social problems, in one of the world's most populous cities by 1914. The dislocation of war and the trauma of economic depression gave further impetus to the quest for solutions, which took dramatic (if controversial) shape in post-1945 planning policies. Contemporary Glasgow thus bears the legacy of twentieth-century industrial decline as well as cultural renewal, although Glasgow shows that there is nothing novel about regeneration strategy in a city which has a long tradition of blending innovation with historical continuity.Beautifully illustrated with over 100 photographs, this vibrant book offers the reader an unparalleled insight to the development of this wonderful city.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 4aScottish Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh1 aConstantine, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEdinburgh University Press Backlist eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311078046840uhttps://doi.org/10.15